body:
Fixes https://github.com/ruffle-rs/ruffle/issues/7587 .

The issue was that the script does
```js
   startDrag(obj,0);
   stopDrag();
   return eval(obj._dropTarget);
```
and we never got the opportunity to call `update_drag()` to set `obj._dropTarget`. I tested that FP7 sets `obj._dropTarget` after `stop` was called (but, weirdly, not immediately after `start` was called).

This migrates all existing events to AS.

Example diff of event creation:

```rs
                        let mut io_error_evt = Avm2Event::new(
                            "ioError",
                            Avm2EventData::IOError {
                                text: "Error #2032: Stream Error".into(),
                                error_id: 2032,
                            },
                        );
                        io_error_evt.set_bubbles(false);
                        io_error_evt.set_cancelable(false);
                        let io_error_evt = EventObject::from_event(&mut activation, io_error_evt)?;
```
->
```rs
                        let io_error_evt_cls = activation.avm2().classes().ioerrorevent;
                        let io_error_evt = io_error_evt_cls.construct(
                            &mut activation,
                            &[
                                "ioError".into(),
                                false.into(),
                                false.into(),
                                "Error #2032: Stream Error".into(),
                                2032.into(),
                            ],
                        )?;
```
and for "simple events" one can skip jumping into AS constructor entirely:
```rs
        let mut removed_evt = Avm2Event::new("removed", Avm2EventData::Empty);
        removed_evt.set_bubbles(true);
        removed_evt.set_cancelable(false);
        let removed_evt = EventObject::from_event(&mut activation, removed_evt)?;
```
->
```rs
        let removed_evt = Avm2EventObject::bare_event(context, "removed", true, false);
```
Upsides:
- way less code
- way less duplication
- faster builds c:
- relatively trivial to add new events... as long as they don't happen to require native fields.

Downsides:
- had to make a custom method to create `EventObject`s without `construct`, to avoid constructing an `Activation`.
  - In general, this is slowly becoming a bit of a mess - `broadcast_event_object` creates an `Activation`, then passes its `.context` to `dispatch_event_object`, which creates _another_ `Activation`... ew. Maybe we should refactor the APIs a bit to have a nicer split between an "vm state" we can use at any time, and "AS interpreter" (Activation) that's only created if we actually execute bytecode...?
- will unavoidably be slightly slower, both construction and field accesses from Rust (will become better if we implement Rust-level precompiled known slot access)
- ugly at places; **especially** `EventObject::mouse_event` is ugly IMO. Opinions welcome :) And in general, passing 5+ positional args is less readable than creating an `EventData` with named fields.
- `ActionType::Event2` doesn't really play well with this; I had to limit its functionality to only create `Event` instances (no subclasses), which is enough for now, but might be an issue in the future.
